      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that originalism rolls back rights is often a misunderstanding of how the text was actually written at the time of ratification, which frequently excluded groups like women and enslaved people. A \"living\" Constitution approach is essentially judicial activism where unelected judges rewrite the law based on their own values, effectively bypassing the democratic process. Originalism actually protects rights by tethering them to the specific promises made by the Founders, whereas a living interpretation allows judges to expand rights arbitrarily without public debate or amendment.",
      "source": "target",
